      <Subject xmlns="urn:xmlns:nl:pop-project:vocab:Subjects#">D36000</Subject>
      <Abstract xml:lang="en">A fundamental feature of natural language is that it allows us to reproduce what others have said. Philosophers, cognitive scientists, and linguists universally acknowledge the central role of speech reporting in language. It is therefore remarkable that current linguistic/semantic research has focused entirely on a single, specific subtype: indirect speech reporting. Linguists disqualify all constructions involving quotation marks as "unnatural", despite their ubiquity in all forms of language use. On the other hand, quotation has always attracted a fair amount of attention from philosophers of language and recent years have even seen a new surge of interest in the topic. Philosophers are now turning their attention to the grey area between direct and indirect speech, scare quoting and mixed quotation, in which a speaker uses quotation marking to echo only a particular phrase or word from an earlier utterance. My aim is to bring together the current insights from philosophy with state of the art linguistic and logical semantic tools. Providing such an interdisciplinary approach to quotation is a much needed and natural follow-up of the traditional semantic focus on indirect reporting, the topic of my dissertation, which is likewise situated at the intersection of philosophy, logic and linguistics.</Abstract>
